  "author_association": "MEMBER",
  "body": "**(SEE UPDATE at https://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes/issues/52202#issuecomment-329888449)**\r\n\r\nCurrently, if you're writing an initializer controller, you're most likely using it to initialize a `Pod` and deploying the controller with `Deployment`. Therefore you're likely using the following trick to avoid the chicken and egg problem:\r\n\r\n```yaml\r\nmetadata:\r\n  initializers:\r\n    pending: []\r\n```\r\n\r\nThis bypasses the initializers for the pods and lets your controller to be deployed even though your InitializerConfiguration is configured to capture all pods.\r\n\r\nProblem occurs when you **apply an update** to this Deployment with the same manifest containing empty pending list. You get error:\r\n\r\n```\r\nThe Deployment \"my-initializer\" is invalid: metadata.initializers:\r\nInvalid value: \"null\": field is immutable once initialization has completed\r\n```\r\n\r\nI think this is a somewhat major UX issue. It requires users to deploy the initializer controller with the `metadata.initializers.pending=[]` but later on when they need to update the controller with `kubectl apply`, they can't use the same manifest containing the empty list.\r\n\r\n/area api\r\n/area extensibility\r\n/sig api-machinery\r\n/kind bug\r\n/assign @caesarxuchao ",
